  1. To view the distribution of discrete variables like continent, try generating a bar chart that counts the number of observations of each continent in the dataset. Once you have this generated, try setting fill = continent within the global aesthetics & see how your visualization changes.
ggplot(gapminder, aes(x = continent)) +
  geom_bar()

ggplot(gapminder, aes(x = continent, fill = continent)) +
  geom_bar()

  1. What is the distribution of life_expectancy over the whole data set? (Hint: use the geom_density layer, after mapping the x-variable to life_expectancy)
ggplot(gapminder, aes(x = life_expectancy)) +
  geom_density()

  1. Can we group this by continent? Try setting “fill = continent” after “x = life_expectancy”. (Hint: geom_density(alpha = 0.5) makes the density distributions transparent).
ggplot(gapminder, aes(x = life_expectancy, fill = continent)) +
  geom_density(alpha = 0.5)

  1. How has life_expectancy changed over the years, year, by continent? Try fitting this first with a scatter plot, and then with a ‘lm’ smoother to see two different ways of visualizing this. (Hint: one is much simpler on the eye!)
ggplot(data = gapminder) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = year, y = life_expectancy, color = continent), method = 'lm')

Data Manipulation Exercises

  1. Extract data from the gapminder dataset that contains the following information:
  • Country: Belize
  • Year: 1990
  • Life_expectancy
  • Population
  • Continent
gapminder %>% filter(country == c('Belize')) %>%
  filter(year == 1990) %>%
  select(country, year, life_expectancy, population, continent)
##   country year life_expectancy population continent
## 1  Belize 1990            71.4     187552  Americas
  1. Maybe we’re interested in calculating the gross domestic product per capita. Use the mutate function & write an expression to calculate this, and create a new column in the dataframe. (Hint: gdp / population)
gapminder %>% mutate(gdp_percap = gdp / population) %>%
  select(country, year, gdp, population, gdp_percap) %>% 
  head
##               country year          gdp population gdp_percap

  1. Build on your code from question 2, and find out the top 3 GDP per capita in each continent (Hint: use %>% head(3) at the end to only select the top 3).
# Descending gdp_percap for Africa
gapminder %>% mutate(gdp_percap = gdp / population) %>%
  filter(continent == 'Africa') %>%
  arrange(desc(gdp_percap)) %>% 
  select(continent, country, year, population, gdp, gdp_percap) %>% 
  head(3)
##   continent           country year population        gdp gdp_percap
## 1    Africa Equatorial Guinea 2011     750918 6403432391   8527.472
## 2    Africa Equatorial Guinea 2009     707155 6024744206   8519.694
## 3    Africa        Seychelles 2011      93810  798003690   8506.595
gapminder %>% mutate(gdp_percap = gdp / population) %>%
  filter(continent == 'Europe') %>%
  arrange(desc(gdp_percap)) %>% 
  select(continent, country, year, population, gdp, gdp_percap) %>% 
  head(3)
##   continent    country year population         gdp gdp_percap

library(nycflights13)
data(flights)

data(airlines)

flights_carrier <- flights %>%
  inner_join(airlines, by=c('carrier'='carrier'))

  1. Using the flights_carrier dataset, create a new data set, flights2 that contains the carrier name, year, month, day, departure delay, arrival delay, origin airport, destination airport, and flight number.
flights2 <- select(flights_carrier, carrier, year, month, day, dep_delay, arr_delay, origin, dest, flight)

  1. How many unique flight routes does American Airlines Inc. run departing from the New York area? (Hint: use the n_distinct() command within summarise)
flights2 %>% filter(carrier == 'AA') %>% summarize(n_distinct(flight))
## # A tibble: 1 x 1
##   `n_distinct(flight)`
##                  <int>
## 1                  220
  1. How many unique flight routes does American Airlines Inc. run from each of the three area airports?
flights2 %>% filter(carrier == 'AA') %>% group_by(origin) %>% summarize(n_distinct(flight))
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##   origin `n_distinct(flight)`
##   <chr>                 <int>
## 1 EWR                      30
## 2 JFK                      92
## 3 LGA                     102
  1. What is the average departure delay of a American Airlines Inc. flight leaving JFK? LGA? EWR? What about leaving any New York area airport?
# Mean for each origin
flights2 %>% filter(carrier == 'UA') %>% filter(dep_delay != 'NA') %>% group_by(origin) %>% summarize(mean=mean(dep_delay))
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##   origin  mean
##   <chr>  <dbl>
## 1 EWR     12.5
## 2 JFK      7.9
## 3 LGA     12.1
#Mean for any New York airport
flights2 %>% filter(carrier == 'UA') %>% filter(dep_delay != 'NA') %>% summarize(mean=mean(dep_delay))
